The better world is already here.
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world where fewer resources mean more people, where increasing resource needs lead to plundering and war, and where the growing production capacity of the last decades brings about more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, "The Limits to Growth," continues to influence the environmental movement to this day.
The optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, living standards, environmental quality, and so forth.
They are seen by their opponents as "economists of abundance," who trust a market that allegedly solves all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see if the world is really getting better or worse.
That is exactly what I have tried to achieve together with 21 globally leading economists by developing a valuation list spanning the last 150 years.
In ten areas—ranging from health, education, war, gender ratio, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity—economists have all answered the same question: how high were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including projections up to 2050.
Based on classical economic assessments of all factors from fatalities, health damages, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands up to higher hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists break down the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the magnitude of the problem, it will be compared with the resources available for its solution.
Through this, the size of the problem is clearly shown as a percentage of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 have been partly surprising.
Let's consider the gender inequality.
At the core, we excluded almost half of the world's population from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the worldwide workforce were female.
What losses have arisen from this small proportion?
Even if we account for the higher costs incurred by educating women, and that someone has to bear the burden of unpaid domestic work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the global GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female participation rate in the workforce and smaller income differences, the loss stands at 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It is likely to be surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to largely bring an increasing net benefit – rising up to 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefits outweigh the drawbacks.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 entries were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, a mild warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces the heating demand more significantly than it creates new cooling demand, which amounts to an advantage of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, the warming leads to water shortages, which cost about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems like wetlands, resulting in a loss of about 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, costs increase and benefits decrease, dramatically lowering the net benefit.
By 2070, global warming will impose net costs on the world, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the rating list also shows us that the world's biggest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
More than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution due to harmful gases from cooking and heating. This corresponds to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
However, in the year 1900, these costs amounted to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will decrease to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved the most worldwide.
Up until the late 18th century, human life expectancy had barely changed.
The size of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overstated: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is at 69 years (and likely to be 76 years by 2050).
The greatest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
For example, as late as 1970, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which had led to the rescue of three million lives annually – more than would have been saved worldwide through peace in the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.   Note: The word "Eltern" in German can mean both "parents" (plural) and "parent(s)" (singular), depending on the context. In this translation, I've used the plural form "parents" as it is more common in English when referring to multiple people who are proud of a shared success. If you meant to refer to a single parent or pair of parents, please let me know, and I can adjust the translation accordingly.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised an additional 10 billion USD.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, the cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, at the beginning of the twentieth century, the costs associated with poorer health amounted to surprising 32% of the global GDP.
Today, they have decreased to about 11%, and will halve again by 2050.
Even though the optimists are not entirely correct in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century likely cost about 1% of GDP annually, and in some places much more), the overall picture is clear.
The majority of the topics examined show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even more pronounced.
Compared to the resources available for combating them, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no problems anymore.
Even though they have diminished in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they remain significant issues nonetheless.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has significantly improved.
Moreover, the rating list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not shape our view of the future based on the most terrifying stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather on objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
